    <section>
        <h>dependents</h>
        <section id="subject">
            <h>subject</h>
            <p>The subject of <g>sgrìobh</g> is generally human.</p>
            <p>Older pedagogical examples – <xl id="sbj-older-pedag">
                    <li>
                        <gd><m>Tha <u>mo mhàthair</u> a’ sgrìobhadh</m> litreach gu m’athair a tha
                            air falbh.</gd>
                        <tr>My mother is writing a letter to my father who is away.</tr>
                        <ref text="621">td. 5</ref>
                    </li>
                </xl>
            </p>
        </section>
        <section id="object">
            <h>object</h>
            <p>The object of <g>sgrìobh</g> is generally an inscribed information object – <ul>
                    <li><g>sgrìobh <a href="?gd=litir">litir</a></g>
                        <en>write a letter</en></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>The object can be omitted if understood from context – <ul>
                    <li>pedagogical examples – <xl id="intrans-pedag">
                            <li>
                                <gd>Sgrìobh e thugam.</gd>
                                <tr>He wrote [a letter, an email, ...] to me.</tr>
                                <ref text="601">td. 347</ref>
                            </li>
                        </xl></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </section>
        <section id="complements">
            <h>complements</h>
            <p>The intended recipient can be introduced by the preposition <a
                    href="?gd=gu^preposition"><g>gu</g></a>
                <en>to</en> – <ul>
                    <li>pedagogical examples – <xl id="gu-pedag">
                            <li>
                                <gd>Sgrìobh e litir ghoirid <m>gu caraid dha</m>. | Sgrìobh e
                                        <m>thugam</m>.</gd>
                                <tr>He wrote a short letter to a friend of his. | He wrote to
                                    me.</tr>
                                <ref text="601">td. 346–7</ref>
                            </li>
                        </xl>
                    </li>
                    <li>older pedagogical examples – <xl id="gu-older-pedag">
                            <li>
                                <gd>Tha mo mhàthair a’ sgrìobhadh litreach <m>gu m’athair</m> a tha
                                    air falbh.</gd>
                                <tr>My mother is writing a letter to my father who is away.</tr>
                                <ref text="621">td. 5</ref>
                            </li>
                        </xl>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </section>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h>uses</h>
        <section>
            <h>derivatives</h>
            <module id="sgriobhadh">
                <h>sgrìobhadh</h>
                <p><g>sgrìobhadh</g>
                    <en>writing</en> is a masculine common noun, derived with suffix <a href="?gd=_adh"><g>-adh</g></a>.</p>
                <section id="sgriobhadh-forms">
                    <h>forms</h>
                    <p>The principal parts of <g>sgrìobhadh</g> are – <ul>
                            <li><m>sgrìobhadh</m> – nominative/dative singular</li>
                            <li><m>sgrìobhaidh</m> – genitive singular</li>
                            <li><m>sgrìobhaidhean</m> – plural</li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                    <section id="definiteness">
